# Copy this file to .env (gitignored) and fill in real values.
#
# These comments are living documentation: each token's block spells out the
# exact permissions and creation steps so it can be regenerated from scratch.
# Any change to a token's required scope (e.g. adding D1) must update the
# comment here in the same commit.
#
# Loading: wrangler reads .env natively. The agent container injects these
# vars via `docker --env-file .env`; on host machines, source them yourself
# (e.g. direnv, or `set -a; . ./.env; set +a`) for tools other than wrangler.
# Worker *runtime* secrets do NOT go here — they go in .dev.vars locally and
# `npx wrangler secret put` in production.
#
# GitHub auth on the host needs no token: local sessions push over SSH and use
# the gh keyring login; cloud sessions get repo-scoped credentials from the
# Claude GitHub App; CI uses the built-in GITHUB_TOKEN. GH_TOKEN below exists
# for the one surface with none of those: the isolated agent container
# (./bin/claude), which has no SSH keys or keyring.

# ── CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# Purpose: lets wrangler deploy the Worker non-interactively (local machines
# with a `wrangler login` OAuth session don't need it).
# Where this token lives (keep all copies in sync when rotating):
#   1. This file's sibling .env on Connor's machine (local + Dispatch deploys)
#   2. GitHub Actions repo secret CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN on couetilc/news
#      (canonical deploy path: merge to main → CI deploys). Rotate with:
#      grep '^CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=' .env | cut -d= -f2- | gh secret set CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN
#   NOT in the claude.ai cloud environment — it is deliberately credential-free
#   (cloud sessions test + push branches; CI deploys). See
#   .claude/skills/agentic-environments/SKILL.md.
# Regenerate at: https://dash.cloudflare.com/profile/api-tokens
#   → Create Token → template "Edit Cloudflare Workers", scoped as below.
# Actual grants of the current token (created 2026-06-10):
#   Account ("Connor@couetil.com's Account", id dbaa50e60c18b19d483578c42d9bb3ee):
#     • Workers Scripts: Edit               (required: deploy code, versions, secrets)
#     • Workers KV Storage: Edit            (required: SESSION KV auto-provisioned on deploy)
#     • D1: Edit                            (required: NEWS_DB feed database; added 2026-06-13)
#     • Workers R2 Storage: Edit            (required on BOTH this local .env AND the
#                                            GH Actions repo secret: the news-cdn R2
#                                            bucket is an r2_buckets binding in
#                                            wrangler.jsonc, auto-provisioned on the CI
#                                            deploy — so CI needs R2 read/write +
#                                            provisioning, not just local. The same scope
#                                            also lets scripts/upload-screenshot.sh push
#                                            PR screenshots from a dev/agent session.
#                                            ⚠️ Must be set BEFORE the binding deploys, or
#                                            that deploy fails on auto-provision.)
#     • Workers Observability: Edit         (observability is enabled in wrangler.jsonc)
#     • Workers Tail: Read                  (npx wrangler tail)
#     • Workers Builds Configuration: Edit  (Workers Builds CI; unused today)
#     • Workers Agents Configuration: Edit  (unused today)
#     • Cloudflare Pages: Edit              (unused — this project deploys Workers, not Pages)
#     • Containers: Edit                    (unused today)
#     • Account Settings: Read              (account discovery/verification)
#   Zone (only cuteteal.com, id 1413a4570fa6e193d5f224ebb5220bb5):
#     • Workers Routes: Edit                (required: custom domain news.cuteteal.com)
#   All users:
#     • User Details: Read, Memberships: Read  (wrangler whoami / account listing)
#   Fallback: if custom-domain attach fails on permissions, add Zone → DNS: Edit.
CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=

# ── CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Purpose: authenticates the claude CLI inside the agent container
# (./bin/claude). The host stores Claude credentials in the macOS Keychain,
# which containers cannot read; this long-lived token is the container path.
# Regenerate with: `claude setup-token` on the host (browser flow; valid ~1
# year; inference-only scope; requires Pro/Max subscription). Paste the
# printed token here.
CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN=

# ── Codex auth (./bin/codex) ─────────────────────────────────────────
# The codex CLI in the agent container authenticates with your ChatGPT
# *subscription*, not pay-as-you-go API billing — for parity with ./bin/claude,
# which bills the Claude subscription via CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN. This needs
# NOTHING in .env: run `codex login` once on this host (browser OAuth against
# your ChatGPT plan), and bin/codex injects the resulting ~/.codex/auth.json
# into the container (the browser login can't run under the no-host-mount
# contract). Codex usage then draws on your plan's limits at no extra charge.
#
# ── OPENAI_API_KEY (optional fallback) ───────────────────────────────
# Purpose: an OPTIONAL fallback for ./bin/codex. Set it ONLY if you'd rather
# bill Codex usage pay-as-you-go at API token rates (a separate charge from your
# ChatGPT subscription — the two do not offset each other) instead of using the
# `codex login` subscription credential above. The entrypoint runs
# `codex login --api-key` with it when no injected subscription auth is present.
# Regenerate at: https://platform.openai.com/api-keys
#   → Create new secret key. OpenAI has no "inference-only" preset like claude's
#   token; keys are either Default (full project access) or Restricted. For a
#   least-privilege key, choose Restricted and grant only "Model capabilities:
#   Write" (the model.request scope) — though restricted keys have had friction
#   with the Responses API that Codex uses, so a Default project key on an
#   account with gpt-5.5 access is the reliable choice.
# Only consumed by ./bin/codex (the agent container). Host/cloud/CI don't use
# it — the claude.ai cloud environment stays deliberately credential-free, and
# CI deploys via CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN, not Codex.
OPENAI_API_KEY=

# ── GH_TOKEN ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Purpose: REQUIRED by the agent container (./bin/claude), which has no SSH
# keys or gh keyring: it clones the repo from GitHub at launch and pushes
# branches / opens PRs over HTTPS with this token.
# (Host sessions don't need it — SSH + keyring; don't export it globally.)
# Regenerate at: https://github.com/settings/personal-access-tokens
#   → Fine-grained token → Resource owner: couetilc → Only select
#   repositories: couetilc/news → Repository permissions:
#     • Metadata: Read                (mandatory baseline)
#     • Contents: Read and write      (clone, push)
#     • Pull requests: Read and write (open/update PRs, queue auto-merge)
#     • Issues: Read and write        (the backlog lives in GitHub issues)
#     • Actions: Read                 (gh run list/watch/view --log — agents
#                                      watch CI and debug failures)
#   Optional: Commit statuses: Read — only needed for `gh pr checks`, which
#   GitHub's PAT UI can't otherwise satisfy (no "Checks" permission exists);
#   the gh run commands above cover CI watching without it.
#   Not yet needed: Workflows: Read and write (only if the container must
#   edit .github/workflows files — prefer doing that from the host).
GH_TOKEN=
